Think carefully about the problem of designing meaningful Core Web Vitals performance budgets for different site types and use cases. The Google-defined thresholds (LCP under 2.5s, INP under 200ms, CLS under 0.1) are universal — they apply equally to a personal blog, a complex e-commerce checkout flow, an interactive data visualization tool, and a news article. But these different site types have radically different performance characteristics and user expectations.

Consider: a static content site (blog, documentation) can realistically achieve LCP under 1.5s and near-zero CLS with proper image sizing, whereas a rich interactive application (online IDE, collaborative document editor, financial dashboard) may structurally require more JavaScript execution and accept higher INP in exchange for richer functionality. Are the universal Core Web Vitals thresholds the right targets for all site types, or are they calibrated for the median web page in a way that creates unrealistic expectations for legitimate complex applications?

Reason through the concept of user-type-adjusted budgets: a page viewed primarily on high-end desktop devices on fast connections has a different performance context than one viewed on mid-range Android devices on 4G connections. CrUX data is segmented by device type for this reason. What is the right unit of performance measurement — 75th percentile of all users, 75th percentile of mobile users, or some other aggregation?

Consider the feedback loop between performance measurement and engineering behavior. If a team has a CLS budget of 0.05, they will instrument their CI pipeline to reject deployments that exceed it. What are the perverse incentives this creates — are there legitimate UX choices that increase CLS (accordion expand, in-page navigation, dynamic content insertion) that an overly strict CLS budget would discourage?

Propose a framework for setting performance budgets that is calibrated to site type, user context, and business criticality, while remaining actionable and automatable.
